        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Pediatric Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Oct 1 2020</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name">Contrast-enhanced US in Pediatric Patients: Overview of Bowel Applications</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Ami</span> <span property="familyName">Gokli</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD, MSEd</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8123-6637" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8123-6637</a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#74331b1f181d15341119151d185a171c1b045a111001" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="55123a3e393c34153038343c397b363d3a257b303120">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Michael R.</span> <span property="familyName">Acord</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8575-0983" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0001-8575-0983</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Misun</span> <span property="familyName">Hwang</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0125-2686" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0125-2686</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Alexandra</span> <span property="familyName">Medellin-Kowalewski</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Erika</span> <span property="familyName">Rubesova</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Sudha A.</span> <span property="familyName">Anupindi</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7784-3108" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7784-3108</a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">40</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">6</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020200019" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020200019</a></div></div><div class="core-relations my-3"><div class="relation mb-3"><div class="relation--head"><i class="icon-info"></i><a href="/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200193">See related article</a></div></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Contrast material–enhanced US is a technique that is approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for the characterization of liver lesions and intravesicular applications in children; however, contrast-enhanced US has several other pediatric applications in clinical practice. The most common application is for patients with inflammatory bowel disease (IBD). Contrast-enhanced US can be used to diagnose IBD, distinguish regions of active or chronic inflammation of the bowel wall, and evaluate associated complications such as abscesses, fistulas, and strictures. Dynamic contrast material evaluation provides qualitative and quantitative information about mural and mesenteric blood flow, which is essential in the determination of disease activity in these patients. It also has the potential to provide a means of monitoring the response to therapy beyond endoscopy or MR enterography. In addition to its use for IBD, contrast-enhanced US can be used to assess for bowel perfusion when problem solving in patients with necrotizing enterocolitis, neonatal bowel infarction, or intussusception. It is a useful imaging technique to fortify diagnoses that may otherwise be indeterminate, such as appendicitis, epiploic appendagitis, intraluminal bowel masses, and complex cysts. Finally, innovative applications such as shear-wave elastography have the potential to provide information about the stiffness of the bowel wall.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div><div role="paragraph">See discussion on this article by <a href="https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2020200193">Watson and Humphries</a>.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200019">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020200019">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="US contrast agent pharmacokinetics. The contrast agent travels proximally from the extremity veins to the heart, into the pulmonary arteries and veins, and then into the systemic circulation, reaching the bowel wall vasculature. After minutes of circulation, the shell breaks down and the inner gas is eliminated from the body through expiration. The outer shell is phagocytosed by macrophages, predominantly in the liver. CEUS = contrast-enhanced US, IV = intravenous line. (Reprinted, with permission, from the Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, ©2020, all rights reserved.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig1.jpeg" height="2807" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. US contrast agent pharmacokinetics. The contrast agent travels proximally from the extremity veins to the heart, into the pulmonary arteries and veins, and then into the systemic circulation, reaching the bowel wall vasculature. After minutes of circulation, the shell breaks down and the inner gas is eliminated from the body through expiration. The outer shell is phagocytosed by macrophages, predominantly in the liver. <i>CEUS</i> = contrast-enhanced US, <i>IV</i> = intravenous line. (Reprinted, with permission, from the Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, ©2020, all rights reserved.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel in an 8-year-old boy. (a) Gray-scale US image shows the cecum, terminal ileum, and ileocecal valve (ICV). (b) Gray-scale US image shows normal wall thickness of less than 3 mm. (c) Color Doppler US image shows normal bowel wall perfusion (arrow), although normal bowel wall does not always show color Doppler US flow."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig2a.jpeg" height="1261" width="1569" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Normal bowel in an 8-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the cecum, terminal ileum, and ileocecal valve <i>(ICV)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows normal wall thickness of less than 3 mm. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler US image shows normal bowel wall perfusion (arrow), although normal bowel wall does not always show color Doppler US flow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel in an 8-year-old boy. (a) Gray-scale US image shows the cecum, terminal ileum, and ileocecal valve (ICV). (b) Gray-scale US image shows normal wall thickness of less than 3 mm. (c) Color Doppler US image shows normal bowel wall perfusion (arrow), although normal bowel wall does not always show color Doppler US flow."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig2b.jpeg" height="1261" width="1581" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Normal bowel in an 8-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the cecum, terminal ileum, and ileocecal valve <i>(ICV)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows normal wall thickness of less than 3 mm. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler US image shows normal bowel wall perfusion (arrow), although normal bowel wall does not always show color Doppler US flow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel in an 8-year-old boy. (a) Gray-scale US image shows the cecum, terminal ileum, and ileocecal valve (ICV). (b) Gray-scale US image shows normal wall thickness of less than 3 mm. (c) Color Doppler US image shows normal bowel wall perfusion (arrow), although normal bowel wall does not always show color Doppler US flow."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig2c.jpeg" height="1276" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Normal bowel in an 8-year-old boy. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows the cecum, terminal ileum, and ileocecal valve <i>(ICV)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows normal wall thickness of less than 3 mm. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler US image shows normal bowel wall perfusion (arrow), although normal bowel wall does not always show color Doppler US flow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Bowel inflammation in a 12-year-old girl. (a) Gray-scale US image of the ascending colon shows marked thickening (+) of the bowel wall of greater than 3 mm. The echogenic submucosal layer is often the thickest layer. (b) Color Doppler US image shows associated hyperemia in the bowel wall and the surrounding mesentery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig3a.jpeg" height="1460" width="1463" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Bowel inflammation in a 12-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image of the ascending colon shows marked thickening (+) of the bowel wall of greater than 3 mm. The echogenic submucosal layer is often the thickest layer. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows associated hyperemia in the bowel wall and the surrounding mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Bowel inflammation in a 12-year-old girl. (a) Gray-scale US image of the ascending colon shows marked thickening (+) of the bowel wall of greater than 3 mm. The echogenic submucosal layer is often the thickest layer. (b) Color Doppler US image shows associated hyperemia in the bowel wall and the surrounding mesentery."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig3b.jpeg" height="1460" width="1487" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Bowel inflammation in a 12-year-old girl. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image of the ascending colon shows marked thickening (+) of the bowel wall of greater than 3 mm. The echogenic submucosal layer is often the thickest layer. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows associated hyperemia in the bowel wall and the surrounding mesentery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Active inflammation of the bowel in a 4-year-old boy with 2 weeks of bloody stool and abdominal pain but stable laboratory results who presented for suspicion of newly active disease. (a) Sagittal gray-scale US image of the rectum shows concentric bowel wall thickening (+) of 0.45 cm and increased echogenicity of surrounding mesenteric fat. (b) Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the wall (arrow), a finding indicative of active inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig4a.jpeg" height="1715" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Active inflammation of the bowel in a 4-year-old boy with 2 weeks of bloody stool and abdominal pain but stable laboratory results who presented for suspicion of newly active disease. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image of the rectum shows concentric bowel wall thickening (+) of 0.45 cm and increased echogenicity of surrounding mesenteric fat. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the wall (arrow), a finding indicative of active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Active inflammation of the bowel in a 4-year-old boy with 2 weeks of bloody stool and abdominal pain but stable laboratory results who presented for suspicion of newly active disease. (a) Sagittal gray-scale US image of the rectum shows concentric bowel wall thickening (+) of 0.45 cm and increased echogenicity of surrounding mesenteric fat. (b) Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the wall (arrow), a finding indicative of active inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig4b.jpeg" height="1715" width="1220" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Active inflammation of the bowel in a 4-year-old boy with 2 weeks of bloody stool and abdominal pain but stable laboratory results who presented for suspicion of newly active disease. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image of the rectum shows concentric bowel wall thickening (+) of 0.45 cm and increased echogenicity of surrounding mesenteric fat. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the wall (arrow), a finding indicative of active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic" aria-label="Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in a) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in b), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig5a.jpeg" height="870" width="1833" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in <b>a</b>) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in a) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in b), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig5b.jpeg" height="870" width="1917" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in <b>a</b>) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in a) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in b), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig5c.jpeg" height="950" width="1851" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in <b>a</b>) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5d" class="graphic" aria-label="Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in a) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in b), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig5d.jpeg" height="950" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig5d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span>. Persistent enhancement in a 4-year-old boy with active inflammation. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show quick rectal wall wash-in (arrow in <b>a</b>) and transmural hyperenhancement (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>), which avidly persists through 30 seconds and begins to wash out at approximately 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is also hyperenhancing. These findings are consistent with active inflammation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig5d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig6a.jpeg" height="900" width="1914" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig6b.jpeg" height="900" width="1824" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig6c.jpeg" height="948" width="1927" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic" aria-label="Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig6d.jpeg" height="948" width="1824" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. Normal bowel perfusion. Multiple still clips from gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) cine US show normal rectal wall wash-in at approximately 30 seconds and normal mural enhancement, which is in the process of washing out at 50 seconds. The surrounding mesentery is normally enhancing.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Time-intensity curve for quantification of disease activity shows key pharmacokinetic parameters after injection of a contrast material bolus. These curves are best calculated directly from the US machine or by using manufacturer-specific software. A range of perfusion kinetics can be obtained from curve analysis. Peak enhancement, AUC, and time to peak are considered the main parameters analyzed for determination of disease. (Reprinted, with permission, from the Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, ©2020, all rights reserved.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig7.jpeg" height="2232" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Time-intensity curve for quantification of disease activity shows key pharmacokinetic parameters after injection of a contrast material bolus. These curves are best calculated directly from the US machine or by using manufacturer-specific software. A range of perfusion kinetics can be obtained from curve analysis. Peak enhancement, AUC, and time to peak are considered the main parameters analyzed for determination of disease. (Reprinted, with permission, from the Children’s Hospital of Philadelphia, ©2020, all rights reserved.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. (a) Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. (b) Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). (c, d) Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum (c), and a time-intensity curve (d). The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig8a.jpeg" height="1109" width="1424" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). <b>(c, d)</b> Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum <b>(c)</b>, and a time-intensity curve <b>(d)</b>. The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. (a) Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. (b) Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). (c, d) Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum (c), and a time-intensity curve (d). The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig8b.jpeg" height="1109" width="1902" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). <b>(c, d)</b> Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum <b>(c)</b>, and a time-intensity curve <b>(d)</b>. The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. (a) Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. (b) Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). (c, d) Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum (c), and a time-intensity curve (d). The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig8c.jpeg" height="1143" width="1969" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). <b>(c, d)</b> Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum <b>(c)</b>, and a time-intensity curve <b>(d)</b>. The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic" aria-label="Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. (a) Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. (b) Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). (c, d) Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum (c), and a time-intensity curve (d). The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig8d.jpeg" height="1143" width="1781" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Chronic inflammation with quantitative evaluation in a 14-year-old adolescent boy who presented with well-managed inflammatory nonpenetrating nonstricturing ileocolonic Crohn disease but had recently elevated fecal calprotectin levels and active inflammation. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows symmetric mural thickening (double-headed arrow) of the terminal ileum that measures 0.50 cm, with loss of stratification. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced US still image shows homogeneous enhancement (arrow) of the thickened bowel that appears similar to that of the surrounding mesentery (*). <b>(c, d)</b> Quantitative analysis shows five regions of interest (circles) along the superficial and deep walls of the terminal ileum <b>(c)</b>, and a time-intensity curve <b>(d)</b>. The postprocessing peak enhancement was calculated to be 12 dB, with a relatively small AUC of 132 arbitrary units (au). This is consistent with chronic inflammation of this segment of bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="NEC in a 5-week-old premature infant who was admitted for abdominal distention and bloody stools. (a) Gray-scale US image of a fixed dilated loop of small bowel in the left upper quadrant shows concentric severe wall thickening (arrows) and surrounding ascites (*). (b) Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the bowel wall (arrow). Additional thickened bowel loops were also visualized (not shown). (c) Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) still images from cine US show concentric wall thickening with surrounding ascites. The contrast-enhanced US image shows marked hyperenhancement of the bowel wall compared with that of the surrounding mesentery and adjacent bowel loops, a finding compatible with the hyperperfusion phase of NEC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig9a.jpeg" height="1253" width="1572" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. NEC in a 5-week-old premature infant who was admitted for abdominal distention and bloody stools. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image of a fixed dilated loop of small bowel in the left upper quadrant shows concentric severe wall thickening (arrows) and surrounding ascites (*). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the bowel wall (arrow). Additional thickened bowel loops were also visualized (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) still images from cine US show concentric wall thickening with surrounding ascites. The contrast-enhanced US image shows marked hyperenhancement of the bowel wall compared with that of the surrounding mesentery and adjacent bowel loops, a finding compatible with the hyperperfusion phase of NEC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="NEC in a 5-week-old premature infant who was admitted for abdominal distention and bloody stools. (a) Gray-scale US image of a fixed dilated loop of small bowel in the left upper quadrant shows concentric severe wall thickening (arrows) and surrounding ascites (*). (b) Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the bowel wall (arrow). Additional thickened bowel loops were also visualized (not shown). (c) Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) still images from cine US show concentric wall thickening with surrounding ascites. The contrast-enhanced US image shows marked hyperenhancement of the bowel wall compared with that of the surrounding mesentery and adjacent bowel loops, a finding compatible with the hyperperfusion phase of NEC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig9b.jpeg" height="1253" width="1579" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. NEC in a 5-week-old premature infant who was admitted for abdominal distention and bloody stools. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image of a fixed dilated loop of small bowel in the left upper quadrant shows concentric severe wall thickening (arrows) and surrounding ascites (*). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the bowel wall (arrow). Additional thickened bowel loops were also visualized (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) still images from cine US show concentric wall thickening with surrounding ascites. The contrast-enhanced US image shows marked hyperenhancement of the bowel wall compared with that of the surrounding mesentery and adjacent bowel loops, a finding compatible with the hyperperfusion phase of NEC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="NEC in a 5-week-old premature infant who was admitted for abdominal distention and bloody stools. (a) Gray-scale US image of a fixed dilated loop of small bowel in the left upper quadrant shows concentric severe wall thickening (arrows) and surrounding ascites (*). (b) Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the bowel wall (arrow). Additional thickened bowel loops were also visualized (not shown). (c) Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) still images from cine US show concentric wall thickening with surrounding ascites. The contrast-enhanced US image shows marked hyperenhancement of the bowel wall compared with that of the surrounding mesentery and adjacent bowel loops, a finding compatible with the hyperperfusion phase of NEC."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig9c.jpeg" height="1150" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. NEC in a 5-week-old premature infant who was admitted for abdominal distention and bloody stools. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image of a fixed dilated loop of small bowel in the left upper quadrant shows concentric severe wall thickening (arrows) and surrounding ascites (*). <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows hyperemia in the bowel wall (arrow). Additional thickened bowel loops were also visualized (not shown). <b>(c)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) still images from cine US show concentric wall thickening with surrounding ascites. The contrast-enhanced US image shows marked hyperenhancement of the bowel wall compared with that of the surrounding mesentery and adjacent bowel loops, a finding compatible with the hyperperfusion phase of NEC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="NEC with adequate bowel perfusion in a 7-month-old male infant who was born prematurely after 33 weeks of gestation. He had a previous diagnosis of NEC and was suspected to have recurrent NEC with a possible bowel infarct. Symptoms included abdominal distention, bloody stools, and inappetence. (a) Gray-scale US image shows echogenic foci in the bowel wall (arrowhead) separate from the bowel lumen (arrow), which is consistent with pneumatosis and confirms the diagnosis of NEC. (b) Dual-screen gray-scale US image (left) and nonenhanced US image with contrast-enhancement settings applied (right) show the bowel wall before contrast material injection (arrowhead, arrow). (c) Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show adequate enhancement of the bowel wall (arrow) compared with adjacent loops (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig10a.jpeg" height="1076" width="1703" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. NEC with adequate bowel perfusion in a 7-month-old male infant who was born prematurely after 33 weeks of gestation. He had a previous diagnosis of NEC and was suspected to have recurrent NEC with a possible bowel infarct. Symptoms included abdominal distention, bloody stools, and inappetence. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows echogenic foci in the bowel wall (arrowhead) separate from the bowel lumen (arrow), which is consistent with pneumatosis and confirms the diagnosis of NEC. <b>(b)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale US image (left) and nonenhanced US image with contrast-enhancement settings applied (right) show the bowel wall before contrast material injection (arrowhead, arrow). <b>(c)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show adequate enhancement of the bowel wall (arrow) compared with adjacent loops (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="NEC with adequate bowel perfusion in a 7-month-old male infant who was born prematurely after 33 weeks of gestation. He had a previous diagnosis of NEC and was suspected to have recurrent NEC with a possible bowel infarct. Symptoms included abdominal distention, bloody stools, and inappetence. (a) Gray-scale US image shows echogenic foci in the bowel wall (arrowhead) separate from the bowel lumen (arrow), which is consistent with pneumatosis and confirms the diagnosis of NEC. (b) Dual-screen gray-scale US image (left) and nonenhanced US image with contrast-enhancement settings applied (right) show the bowel wall before contrast material injection (arrowhead, arrow). (c) Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show adequate enhancement of the bowel wall (arrow) compared with adjacent loops (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig10b.jpeg" height="1276" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. NEC with adequate bowel perfusion in a 7-month-old male infant who was born prematurely after 33 weeks of gestation. He had a previous diagnosis of NEC and was suspected to have recurrent NEC with a possible bowel infarct. Symptoms included abdominal distention, bloody stools, and inappetence. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows echogenic foci in the bowel wall (arrowhead) separate from the bowel lumen (arrow), which is consistent with pneumatosis and confirms the diagnosis of NEC. <b>(b)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale US image (left) and nonenhanced US image with contrast-enhancement settings applied (right) show the bowel wall before contrast material injection (arrowhead, arrow). <b>(c)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show adequate enhancement of the bowel wall (arrow) compared with adjacent loops (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic" aria-label="NEC with adequate bowel perfusion in a 7-month-old male infant who was born prematurely after 33 weeks of gestation. He had a previous diagnosis of NEC and was suspected to have recurrent NEC with a possible bowel infarct. Symptoms included abdominal distention, bloody stools, and inappetence. (a) Gray-scale US image shows echogenic foci in the bowel wall (arrowhead) separate from the bowel lumen (arrow), which is consistent with pneumatosis and confirms the diagnosis of NEC. (b) Dual-screen gray-scale US image (left) and nonenhanced US image with contrast-enhancement settings applied (right) show the bowel wall before contrast material injection (arrowhead, arrow). (c) Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show adequate enhancement of the bowel wall (arrow) compared with adjacent loops (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig10c.jpeg" height="1280" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. NEC with adequate bowel perfusion in a 7-month-old male infant who was born prematurely after 33 weeks of gestation. He had a previous diagnosis of NEC and was suspected to have recurrent NEC with a possible bowel infarct. Symptoms included abdominal distention, bloody stools, and inappetence. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows echogenic foci in the bowel wall (arrowhead) separate from the bowel lumen (arrow), which is consistent with pneumatosis and confirms the diagnosis of NEC. <b>(b)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale US image (left) and nonenhanced US image with contrast-enhancement settings applied (right) show the bowel wall before contrast material injection (arrowhead, arrow). <b>(c)</b> Dual-screen gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show adequate enhancement of the bowel wall (arrow) compared with adjacent loops (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic" aria-label="Total bowel necrosis in a premature newborn girl who was evaluated for possible in utero volvulus at prenatal US (not shown) and found to have duodenal atresia. (a) Gray-scale US image shows echogenic aperistaltic small bowel loops in the mid abdomen (arrowheads), without substantial wall thickening, and a small amount of free fluid with mild complexity manifesting as several septa and echoes (arrows). (b) Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show that after administration of intravenous contrast material, no enhancement of the bowel wall is visible (*), which is consistent with diffuse bowel necrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig11a.jpeg" height="1257" width="1442" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Total bowel necrosis in a premature newborn girl who was evaluated for possible in utero volvulus at prenatal US (not shown) and found to have duodenal atresia. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows echogenic aperistaltic small bowel loops in the mid abdomen (arrowheads), without substantial wall thickening, and a small amount of free fluid with mild complexity manifesting as several septa and echoes (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show that after administration of intravenous contrast material, no enhancement of the bowel wall is visible (*), which is consistent with diffuse bowel necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Total bowel necrosis in a premature newborn girl who was evaluated for possible in utero volvulus at prenatal US (not shown) and found to have duodenal atresia. (a) Gray-scale US image shows echogenic aperistaltic small bowel loops in the mid abdomen (arrowheads), without substantial wall thickening, and a small amount of free fluid with mild complexity manifesting as several septa and echoes (arrows). (b) Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show that after administration of intravenous contrast material, no enhancement of the bowel wall is visible (*), which is consistent with diffuse bowel necrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig11b.jpeg" height="1257" width="2307" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Total bowel necrosis in a premature newborn girl who was evaluated for possible in utero volvulus at prenatal US (not shown) and found to have duodenal atresia. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows echogenic aperistaltic small bowel loops in the mid abdomen (arrowheads), without substantial wall thickening, and a small amount of free fluid with mild complexity manifesting as several septa and echoes (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images show that after administration of intravenous contrast material, no enhancement of the bowel wall is visible (*), which is consistent with diffuse bowel necrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic" aria-label="Equivocal appendicitis in a 10-year-old boy. (a, b) Initial gray-scale (a) and color Doppler (b) US images of the appendix show wall thickening (arrowheads in a) and dilatation, with a diameter of 0.86 cm (dotted line), but no hyperemia. Clinicians were reluctant to proceed to surgery, and MRI could not be performed without sedation. (c) Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images obtained 3 hours later show a hyperenhancing markedly inflamed appendix (arrowhead) with surrounding hyperenhancing mesentery (*). These findings are consistent with appendicitis, which was confirmed surgically."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig12a.jpeg" height="1076" width="1636" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Equivocal appendicitis in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Initial gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images of the appendix show wall thickening (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and dilatation, with a diameter of 0.86 cm (dotted line), but no hyperemia. Clinicians were reluctant to proceed to surgery, and MRI could not be performed without sedation. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images obtained 3 hours later show a hyperenhancing markedly inflamed appendix (arrowhead) with surrounding hyperenhancing mesentery (*). These findings are consistent with appendicitis, which was confirmed surgically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Equivocal appendicitis in a 10-year-old boy. (a, b) Initial gray-scale (a) and color Doppler (b) US images of the appendix show wall thickening (arrowheads in a) and dilatation, with a diameter of 0.86 cm (dotted line), but no hyperemia. Clinicians were reluctant to proceed to surgery, and MRI could not be performed without sedation. (c) Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images obtained 3 hours later show a hyperenhancing markedly inflamed appendix (arrowhead) with surrounding hyperenhancing mesentery (*). These findings are consistent with appendicitis, which was confirmed surgically."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig12b.jpeg" height="1076" width="1308" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Equivocal appendicitis in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Initial gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images of the appendix show wall thickening (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and dilatation, with a diameter of 0.86 cm (dotted line), but no hyperemia. Clinicians were reluctant to proceed to surgery, and MRI could not be performed without sedation. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images obtained 3 hours later show a hyperenhancing markedly inflamed appendix (arrowhead) with surrounding hyperenhancing mesentery (*). These findings are consistent with appendicitis, which was confirmed surgically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic" aria-label="Equivocal appendicitis in a 10-year-old boy. (a, b) Initial gray-scale (a) and color Doppler (b) US images of the appendix show wall thickening (arrowheads in a) and dilatation, with a diameter of 0.86 cm (dotted line), but no hyperemia. Clinicians were reluctant to proceed to surgery, and MRI could not be performed without sedation. (c) Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images obtained 3 hours later show a hyperenhancing markedly inflamed appendix (arrowhead) with surrounding hyperenhancing mesentery (*). These findings are consistent with appendicitis, which was confirmed surgically."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig12c.jpeg" height="1019" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Equivocal appendicitis in a 10-year-old boy. <b>(a, b)</b> Initial gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler <b>(b)</b> US images of the appendix show wall thickening (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and dilatation, with a diameter of 0.86 cm (dotted line), but no hyperemia. Clinicians were reluctant to proceed to surgery, and MRI could not be performed without sedation. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale (left) and contrast-enhanced (right) US images obtained 3 hours later show a hyperenhancing markedly inflamed appendix (arrowhead) with surrounding hyperenhancing mesentery (*). These findings are consistent with appendicitis, which was confirmed surgically.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic" aria-label="SWE and active inflammatory stricture in an 18-year-old male adolescent with Crohn disease and prior ileocolonic resection who presented with symptoms of diarrhea and distention. (a) Gray-scale US image shows mural thickening and a 5-cm region of persistent narrowing (arrows) and upstream dilatation (*) that are consistent with stricture and associated bowel obstruction. (b) Color Doppler US image shows severe hyperemia in the bowel walls at this level (arrow). (c) Contrast-enhanced US image shows severe homogeneous transmural enhancement, with quantification showing peak enhancement of 19 dB and a high AUC, which is consistent with moderate active inflammation. (d) SWE image shows a value of 1.5 m/sec at the area of stricture (arrow), which correlates with low intestinal wall stiffness. These findings are in keeping with a diagnosis of active inflammatory stricture, without substantial fibrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig13a.jpeg" height="1210" width="1534" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. SWE and active inflammatory stricture in an 18-year-old male adolescent with Crohn disease and prior ileocolonic resection who presented with symptoms of diarrhea and distention. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows mural thickening and a 5-cm region of persistent narrowing (arrows) and upstream dilatation (*) that are consistent with stricture and associated bowel obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows severe hyperemia in the bowel walls at this level (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced US image shows severe homogeneous transmural enhancement, with quantification showing peak enhancement of 19 dB and a high AUC, which is consistent with moderate active inflammation. <b>(d)</b> SWE image shows a value of 1.5 m/sec at the area of stricture (arrow), which correlates with low intestinal wall stiffness. These findings are in keeping with a diagnosis of active inflammatory stricture, without substantial fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="SWE and active inflammatory stricture in an 18-year-old male adolescent with Crohn disease and prior ileocolonic resection who presented with symptoms of diarrhea and distention. (a) Gray-scale US image shows mural thickening and a 5-cm region of persistent narrowing (arrows) and upstream dilatation (*) that are consistent with stricture and associated bowel obstruction. (b) Color Doppler US image shows severe hyperemia in the bowel walls at this level (arrow). (c) Contrast-enhanced US image shows severe homogeneous transmural enhancement, with quantification showing peak enhancement of 19 dB and a high AUC, which is consistent with moderate active inflammation. (d) SWE image shows a value of 1.5 m/sec at the area of stricture (arrow), which correlates with low intestinal wall stiffness. These findings are in keeping with a diagnosis of active inflammatory stricture, without substantial fibrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig13b.jpeg" height="1210" width="1815" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. SWE and active inflammatory stricture in an 18-year-old male adolescent with Crohn disease and prior ileocolonic resection who presented with symptoms of diarrhea and distention. <b>(a)</b> Gray-scale US image shows mural thickening and a 5-cm region of persistent narrowing (arrows) and upstream dilatation (*) that are consistent with stricture and associated bowel obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Color Doppler US image shows severe hyperemia in the bowel walls at this level (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced US image shows severe homogeneous transmural enhancement, with quantification showing peak enhancement of 19 dB and a high AUC, which is consistent with moderate active inflammation. <b>(d)</b> SWE image shows a value of 1.5 m/sec at the area of stricture (arrow), which correlates with low intestinal wall stiffness. These findings are in keeping with a diagnosis of active inflammatory stricture, without substantial fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020200019&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic" aria-label="SWE and active inflammatory stricture in an 18-year-old male adolescent with Crohn disease and prior ileocolonic resection who presented with symptoms of diarrhea and distention. (a) Gray-scale US image shows mural thickening and a 5-cm region of persistent narrowing (arrows) and upstream dilatation (*) that are consistent with stricture and associated bowel obstruction. (b) Color Doppler US image shows severe hyperemia in the bowel walls at this level (arrow). (c) Contrast-enhanced US image shows severe homogeneous transmural enhancement, with quantification showing peak enhancement of 19 dB and a high AUC, which is consistent with moderate active inflammation. (d) SWE image shows a value of 1.5 m/sec at the area of stricture (arrow), which correlates with low intestinal wall stiffness. These findings are in keeping with a diagnosis of active inflammatory stricture, without substantial fibrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020200019/asset/images/large/rg.2020200019.fig13c.jpeg" height="1261" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</